WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.960
[Amit Varma]: When we look back at history with the benefit of hindsight, everything can seem inevitable.

00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:14.000
[Amit Varma]: We can look at a seminal moment and it may seem that it was meant to be that way. All

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.600
[Amit Varma]: the currents of history led up to it. And sometimes the future may even have been shaped

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:24.040
[Amit Varma]: by that event. If there was a story to our existence, that event could seem to be a critical

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:29.480
[Amit Varma]: plot point. But then we may look closer and realize that it almost didn't happen, that

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:34.160
[Amit Varma]: a series of lucky accidents took us to that point. And indeed, everything could be said

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:39.160
[Amit Varma]: to be the culmination of a series of accidents. You change one variable somewhere and different

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:43.480
[Amit Varma]: things happen. History changes, humanity changes. If you go back far enough, maybe there's no

00:00:43.480 --> 00:00:48.880
[Amit Varma]: humanity at all. Today's episode is about one such event, a film that seemed to be the

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:54.360
[Amit Varma]: natural progression to all that came before and which shaped all that came after. But

00:00:54.360 --> 00:01:01.400
[Unknown]: it almost didn't happen. Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:11.120
[Unknown]: podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:15.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Uday Bhatia, author of a wonderful

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:20.000
[Amit Varma]: new book called Bullets Over Bombay, Satya and the Hindi Film Gangster. Uday has been

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.120
[Amit Varma]: a film critic for many years, first at Time Out, then at Mint and also on his own blog.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:30.200
[Amit Varma]: He brings a perspective to his criticism which is shaped as much by world cinema as a love

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:34.720
[Amit Varma]: and appreciation of his own culture. Bullets Over Bombay talks about the importance

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:41.280
[Amit Varma]: of Ram Gopal Verma's 1998 film, Satya. In his narrative, Uday traces two parallel traditions

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:46.240
[Amit Varma]: in Hindi cinema. One is the tradition of the gangster film, another is that of the city

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:51.960
[Amit Varma]: man. For Bombay, as it was then, is as much a hero of Satya as Manoj Bajpai or Chakravarti.

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:57.720
[Amit Varma]: And it's fascinating to see how these traditions evolve and come together in this one landmark

00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:00.120
[Amit Varma]: film. Satya is also important because it brought

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:04.840
[Amit Varma]: together a bunch of young, talented people who went on to become stalwarts of the industry

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:10.000
[Amit Varma]: over the next two decades. People like Manoj Bajpai and Anurag Kashyap and no end of names

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:15.480
[Amit Varma]: from the brilliant ensemble cast. At the same time, Satya was shaped by circumstances and

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:21.000
[Amit Varma]: could even be called a product of a series of happy accidents. It's such a great example

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.040
[Amit Varma]: of how history can be shaped by serendipity. I loved this conversation with Uday in which

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:31.440
[Amit Varma]: we also discussed his evolution as a film critic. In some ways, this episode is a natural

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:36.120
[Amit Varma]: follow-up to the episode I recorded a few weeks ago with my good friend Jai Arjun Singh.

00:02:36.120 --> 00:02:40.200
[Amit Varma]: I'll link that from the show notes. Before we get to this conversation though, let's

